{
  "texts": [
    "As for statistical hypothesis testing, early research on private methods can be traced back to the works of Uhlerop et al. (2013) and Vu and Slavkovic (2009).",
    "A significant body of work has since emerged, with one line of research focusing on the design of differentially private versions of popular test statistics for testing goodness-of-fit, closeness, and independence, as well as private ANOVA (Campbell et al., 2018; Couch et al., 2019; Gaboardi, Lim, et al., 2016; Kakizaki et al., 2017; Kifer & Rogers, 2017; Swanberg et al., 2019; Y. Wang et al., 2015).",
    "This line of research specifically looks at the performance of these methods when dealing with small sample sizes.",
    "Another complementary direction of research examines the minimax sample complexity of private hypothesis testing (Acharya, Kamath, et al., 2018; Acharya, Sun, & Zhang, 2018; Aliakbarpour et al., 2018; B. Cai et al., 2017).",
    "Other works in this vein focus on testing of simple hypotheses (Canonne et al., 2019; Cummings et al., 2018)."
  ]
}